04823nam a22006375i 9780520925533DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19981998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209255337 a10.1525/97805209255332doi  a(DE-B1597)648270  a(OCoLC)1414456429  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aB2949.E8bW55 1997eb 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a1932211 aWilliams, Robert R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHegel's Ethics of Recognition /cRobert R. Williams; ed. by Robert R. Williams. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1998] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (450 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- t1 Recognition and Ethics -- tPart One Preliminaries: Recognition, Right, and Ethics -- t2 Recognition in Fichte and Schelling -- t3 Recognition in the Phenomenology of Spirit -- t4 Recognition in the Encyclopedia Philosophy of Spirit -- t5 Recognition and Right in the Jena Manuscripts -- tPart Two Recognition in the Philosophy of Right -- t6 Systematic issues in the Philosophy of Right -- t7 Persons, Property, and Contract -- t8 Crime and Punishment -- t9 Morality -- t10 Ethical Life and the Family -- t11 Civil Society, Poverty, and the Corporations -- t12 Recognition and the Social Contract Theory of the State -- t13 The State as a Social Organism -- t14 Sovereignty, International Relations, and War -- t15 Recent Views of Recognition and the Question Of Ethics -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this significant contribution to Hegel scholarship, Robert Williams develops the most comprehensive account to date of Hegel's concept of recognition (Anerkennung). Fichte introduced the concept of recognition as a presupposition of both Rousseau's social contract and Kant's ethics. Williams shows that Hegel appropriated the concept of recognition as the general pattern of his concept of ethical life, breaking with natural law theory yet incorporating the Aristotelian view that rights and virtues are possible only within a certain kind of community.He explores Hegel's intersubjective concept of spirit (Geist) as the product of affirmative mutual recognition and his conception of recognition as the right to have rights. Examining Hegel's Jena manuscripts, his Philosophy of Right, the Phenomenology of Spirit, and other works, Williams shows how the concept of recognition shapes and illumines Hegel's understandings of crime and punishment, morality, the family, the state, sovereignty, international relations, and war. A concluding chapter on the reception and reworking of the concept of recognition by contemporary thinkers including Derrida, Levinas, and Deleuze demonstrates Hegel's continuing centrality to the philosophical concerns of our age.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthics, Modernx19th century. 0aEthics, Moderny19th century. 0aEthics, Modern. 0aIntersubjectivityxMoral and ethical aspectsxHistoryx19th century. 0aIntersubjectivityxMoral and ethical aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aRecognition (Philosophy)xMoral and ethical aspectsxHistoryx19th century. 0aRecognition (Philosophy)xMoral and ethical aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 4aEthics & Moral Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aWilliams, Robert R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052022492640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092553340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925533